    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "CS(C)=O",
      "C1CCCCC1N=C=NC1CCCCC1",
      "Cl.c1cc[nH+]cc1"
    ],
    "rationale": "This reaction shows the oxidation of a simple primary alcohol (1-butanol) to the corresponding aldehyde (butanal). This is a classic textbook example of the Pfitzner-Moffatt oxidation, utilizing dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) as the oxidant, dicyclohexylcarbodiimide (DCC) as the activator, and pyridinium hydrochloride as the mild acid catalyst. The reactants and products are simple, acyclic, and clearly demonstrate the core transformation without introducing complex or potentially confounding functional groups.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The use of a simple aliphatic alcohol avoids overlap with reactions involving aromatic systems. The specific combination of DMSO, a carbodiimide (DCC), and a mild acid catalyst is characteristic of the Pfitzner-Moffatt protocol, distinguishing it from other activated-DMSO oxidations like the Swern (oxalyl chloride) or Parikh-Doering (SO3-pyridine) oxidations. The structure is kept simple to avoid motifs common in other named reactions."
  }
}
